==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|epyphanie}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|epiphania}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|ἐπιφάνεια||manifestation, striking appearance}}, from {{m|grc|ἐπιφαίνω||I appear, display}}, from {{m|grc|ἐπί||upon}} + {{m|grc|φαίνω||I shine, appear}}. English [[Epiphany]] (of Christ) since the 14th century, generic use since the 17th century.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ɪˈpɪf.ə.ni/|/ɛˈpɪf.ə.ni/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ɪˈpɪf.ə.ni/|/ɨˈpɪf.ə.ni/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-epiphany.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|epiphanies}}

# A [[manifestation]] or [[appearance]] of a [[divine]] or [[superhuman]] [[being]].
# An [[illuminating]] [[realization]] or [[discovery]], often resulting in a personal feeling of [[elation]], [[awe]], or [[wonder]].
# {{label|en|Christianity}} Season or time of the Christian church year from the Epiphany feast day to [[Mardi Gras]] ([[Shrove Tuesday]]), the day before [[Ash Wednesday]], the start of [[Lent]] (See [[Epiphany]]).

====Synonyms====
* {{sense|illuminating realization or discovery}} {{l|en|aha moment}}, {{l|en|enlightenment}}, {{l|en|nirvana}}, {{l|en|satori}}

